item.title: Navalny Arrives in Germany From Siberian Hospital
item.description: A plane carrying opposition politician Alexei Navalny, who was in a coma in a Siberian hospital after suddenly falling ill, landed in Germany where he is meant to undergo treatment after disputes over his condition and whether he was stable enough to travel.

item.title: Mexican President Faces Hard Questions Over Videos of Brother
item.description: Mexican President Andrés Manuel López Obrador, who has made his political bones fighting corruption, found himself denying corruption allegations after two videos emerged showing his younger brother accepting an envelope and a paper bag stuffed with cash in 2015 for the president’s political movement.

item.title: Israel and U.A.E. Get Down to Business
item.description: Investors in Israel and the United Arab Emirates are moving to strike deals in a business environment transformed by a diplomatic breakthrough between the two countries.

item.title: After the Beirut Explosion, Volunteers Step Up to Do What the Government Can't
item.description: Donors say aid will be delivered directly to the people, bypassing the country’s political leadership. But it remains to be seen how successful local groups will be in dealing with such a widespread catastrophe.

item.title: Libya's Rival Governments Declare Cease-Fire
item.description: Libya’s two rival governments declared a cease-fire in the country’s civil war on Friday, easing months of tensions that threatened to draw forces from Turkey, Egypt, Russia and other regional powers into a wider conflict.

item.title: Turkey Looks to Vast Gas Discovery to Bolster Ailing Economy
item.description: Turkey has identified a vast natural gas field in the Black Sea, President Erdogan said, a discovery that could help the country ease its reliance on energy imports.
